This partial document is the third section focusing on the applicable user groups and core usage scenarios of Doubao AI. It first clarifies that Doubao AI has no applicable population restriction, and is adaptable to users of all age groups and all occupations. Then it specifies 5 core applicable user groups and their corresponding high-frequency usage scenarios respectively:
1. Student groups including primary and secondary school students, college students, postgraduate and civil service exam candidates, applicable to scenarios such as knowledge Q&A, homework tutoring, composition writing and correction, paper framework sorting, exam knowledge summarization, study plan formulation, etc.;
2. Office workers including white collars, clerks, managers, sales personnel, operators, etc., applicable to scenarios such as work report writing, meeting minute sorting, PPT outline drafting, email writing, scheme planning, work summary writing, etc.;
3. Content creators including self-media practitioners, copywriters, bloggers, writers, designers, etc., applicable to scenarios such as copywriting, title formulation, script creation, content polishing, topic planning, creative inspiration output, etc.;
4. Ordinary life users including middle-aged and elderly groups, housewives, freelancers, etc., applicable to scenarios such as life common sense consultation, recipe query, travel strategy formulation, health knowledge answer, emotional support, etc.;
5. Professional learners and practitioners including teachers, doctors, programmers, scientific researchers, etc., applicable to scenarios such as teaching courseware writing, professional knowledge interpretation, code writing and debugging, scientific literature sorting, etc.

This partial document is the first section themed "Full coverage of segmented creation scenarios", which mainly introduces that the relevant creation service covers all types of segmented writing demands, and classifies the covered scenarios into 5 major categories with specific typical writing types listed for each category:
1. Daily short copy, including Moments copy, holiday greetings, SMS scripts, blessings, self-introductions, signatures, comments, love words and other daily short writing contents;
2. Workplace office documents, covering work plans, work summaries, meeting minutes, work reports, emails, resignation letters, job application letters, campaign drafts, planning proposals, sales scripts, operation copy and other workplace writing demands;
3. Student-oriented documents, including compositions, after-reading reflections, after-viewing impressions, speech drafts, paper outlines, literature reviews, reading notes, leave notes, proposals and other writing contents for student groups;
4. Creative documents, including self-media copy, short video scripts, live broadcast scripts, novel fragments, poetry, prose, titles, topic selections, advertising slogans, publicity drafts and other creative writing demands;
5. Professional documents, including draft contracts, legal documents, teaching courseware, scientific research reports, code comments, product specifications, project plans and other writing demands for professional fields.

This partial document is a section of summary of commonly used shortcut instructions, which aims to compile high-frequency used shortcut instructions for users to directly copy and modify details to use without manual typing, so as to improve operation efficiency. It divides the shortcut instructions into 4 categories:
1. Creation category, covering instructions for text polishing retaining original meaning with required style, content expansion or reduction to specified word count, and drafting of manuscripts with specified type, theme, style and format;
2. Summary category, covering instructions for summarizing core points of content in bulleted form, and extracting core viewpoints of documents within 100 words;
3. Translation category, covering instructions for translating text to specified language with accurate professional terms, and translating plus polishing foreign language texts to be smooth and natural;
4. Optimization category, covering instructions for correcting grammatical errors and typos of content, and adjusting logical order of content.
